0","about 1350":"circa 1350","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"about 1350–":"about 1350–Deceased","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","about 1380":"about 1380","1350":"1350","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","about 1350":"about 1350","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): from Middle English <i>Gelle</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Gerard</i>. <i>Gerard</i> in Middle English was indistinguishable from <i>Gerald</i>, of which <i>Gelle</i> was a syncopated form.","English: occasionally, a variant of   Gill  , from a pet form of the personal name <i>Jelion</i> or <i>Gillian</i>. These are Middle English versions of <i>Julian</i>, found mainly as a female name, occasionally as a male name.","Manx: variant of   Gill  , a shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille</b>, meaning ‘son of the lad (i.e. servant)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Avtar, Amritpal, Darshan, Hardip, Nirmal, Sohan, Ajit, Balwinder, Charan, Jasvir, Kewal, Navdeep.","English and Scottish: in northern England and Scotland sometimes from Middle English <i>Gille</i>, Old Norse <i>Gilli</i>, which is of Irish (Gaelic) origin (see below), and pronounced with a hard <i>g</i>. As a personal name it is not found after <i>c.</i> 1200.","English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>gille</i> ‘deep glen, ravine’ (Old Norse (Norwegian) <i>gil</i>), pronounced with a hard <i>g</i>. The term is found mainly in northwestern England, where Norwegian Vikings settled."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Gell was born about 1350, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert GYLES I about 1370, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1350":"1350","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1350–":"noin 1350–Kuollut","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","about 1370":"noin 1370","about 1380":"noin 1380","1350":"1350","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","about 1350":"noin 1350","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1350–":"environ 1350–Décédée","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1350–F